Controlling the Container
docker ps: Shows all running containers. Use this to check if your app is "Up" and to see the Port Mapping (e.g., 0.0.0.0:80->80/tcp).

docker stop <id>: Safely stops the container and its processes.

docker rm -f $(docker ps -aq): A "cleanup" command that removes all old or stopped containers to free up space and ports.

Monitoring & Debugging
docker logs <id>: Displays the history of the web app. Use this to check for errors or to see traffic details.

docker attach <id>: Connects your terminal to the live container so you can see changes and logs in real-time.

docker exec -it <id> bash: Lets you "enter" the running container to check files or configurations internally, similar to how you use SSH for an EC2 instance.

Networking & Building
docker network create <name> -d bridge: Creates a private, isolated network for your project so different parts (like backend and database) can talk safely.

docker build -t <image-name> .: Creates a Docker image from your Dockerfile.

docker network inspect: Shows the internal details of a specific network and which containers are connected to it.
